{{Infobox person |name = Watson McMillan Hayes |image = Watson M Hayes.jpg |caption = Watson M. Hayes |birth_date = {{Birth date|1857|11|23}} |birth_place = near Greenfield, [[Mercer County, Pennsylvania|Mercer County]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1944|08|02|1857|11|27}} |death_place = [[Weifang]], [[China]] |nationality = [[United States]] |occupation = [[Mission (Christian)|missionary]], |known_for = Educational Mission in [[China]] |years_active= 62 Years |parents = David Hayes, Margaret Jane Watson Hayes |spouse = Margaret Young Hayes |children = John D. Hayes, Ernest M. Hayes. }}
'''Watson McMillan Hayes''' ({{zh|c={{linktext|赫|士}}|p={{linktext|Hè|shì}}}}, born November 23, 1857 in [[Mercer County, Pennsylvania]] - died August 2, 1944 in Weifang, Shandong) was an American Presbyterian missionary and educator in China.
== Biography == Watson M. Hayes was the son of David Hayes (born April 6, 1832, killed in February 1865 in the [[American Civil War]]) and Margaret Jane (Watson) Hayes (born June 28, 1828). He graduated from [[Allegheny College]]<ref name=pahist>[https://books.google.com/books?id=xB0VAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA902 A twentieth century history of Mercer County, Pennsylvania, Lewis Publishing Company]</ref> and entered Western Seminary, Pittsburgh in 1879.
On August 15, 1882, he was ordained and sent to China in the same year.<ref name=presmindict>[https://books.google.com/books?id=9WXozG4cLPIC&pg=PA301 Biography of Watson McMillan Hayes, The Presbyterian Ministerial Directory, 1898]</ref> He taught at Tengchow College and later served as its president<ref name=lutz1971>Jessie Gregory Lutz, China and the Christian Colleges, 1850-1950, Cornell University Press, Ithaca, New York 1971</ref> in present-day [[Penglai City|Penglai]], [[Shandong]]. In 1901, he was invited by [[Yuan Shikai]] to organize Shandong College,<ref name=heeren1940>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3zYsAAAAIAAJ John J. Heeren (1940): On the Shantung Front, The board of foreign Mission of the presbyterian church in the United States of America]</ref> the forerunner of [[Shandong University]] and the second modern university in China. With the backing of Yuan Shikai, he also published Shandong's first successful newspaper (Shantung Times, {{zh|c={{linktext|山|东|时|报}}|p={{linktext|Shān|dōng |Shí|bào}}}}) and petitioned the Qing court to grant a holiday on Sundays for government schools and colleges;<ref name=1stuniv>[http://www.weihsien-paintings.org/Mprevite/EbaoMonthly/CalvinMateer.htm Qu Zheng-Min, "China's first university"]</ref> Shandong College was closed on Sundays right from the start.<ref name=heeren1940/> However, by the end of 1901, Hayes and six Chinese Christian teachers he had brought with him had resigned already<ref name=heeren1940/> over disagreements regarding the policy of mandatory [[Confucius]] worship for students of the college.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=N7JfoaVbMGgC&pg=PA315 Ulrich van der Heyden (Editor), Holger Stoecker (Editor) 2005: "Mission und Macht im Wandel politischer Orientierungen", Franz Steiner Verlag]</ref> After that, Hayes went on to teach at the Presbyterian Mission Theological College in Cheefoo ([[Yantai]]).
When the Shandong Christian University was formed through an agreement between the Northern Presbyterian mission and the English Baptist mission, Haynes became the dean of the Theological College in 1916.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bdcconline.net/en/stories/h/hayes-watson.php|title=Watson Hayes|last=Stockment|first=Martha|website=Biographical Dictionary of Chinese Christianity|access-date=22 June 2016}}</ref> However, after theological conflicts arose in the college due to the [[Fundamentalist–Modernist Controversy|fundamentalist-modernist controversy]], Haynes was asked to resign in 1919. He would later be appointed as the principal of the newly formed [[North China Theological Seminary]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=The Fundamentalist Movement Among Protestant Missionaries in China, 1920-1937|last=Yao|first=Kevin Xiyi|publisher=University Press of America|year=2003|isbn=9780761827405|location=Lanham, MD|pages=139-182}}</ref>
During the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]], W. M. Hayes, together with his wife (Margaret Young Hayes) and one of his sons (John David Hayes), was held as a prisoner in the [[The Weihsien Compound|Weihsien (Weixian) Internment Camp]], a civilian assembly center operated by the Japanese on the premises of a former Presbyterian mission in the present-day town of [[Weifang]]. Hayes was forced to leave from his home for the camp in March 1943. He refused to be repatriated under the "Prisoners Exchange Project" organized by the International Red Cross. Suffering from [[diabetes]], W. M. Hayes died in the camp on August 2, 1944, a bit more than one year before the camp was liberated by the Americans on August 12, 1945.
W. M. Hayes' son John D. Hayes (1888–1957), continued to work as a missionary and English teacher in China until he was arrested and tried as a spy in 1951. After 10 months in jail, he was expelled from China.<ref name=desertnews>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=336&dat=19530310&id=3CwhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=x3oFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3029,1366856 "China-Born American Sees Mao-Russ Rift", ''Desert News and Telegram'', March 10, 1953]</ref> His trial in China was the topic of an article ("The Brainwashing of John Hayes", written by Frederic Sondern, Jr) published in ''[[Readers Digest]]'' (July 1955) and a television drama of the same title (teleplay by George Bruce, aired on [[TV Reader's Digest]] by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on 7 November 1955) in which Hayes was portrayed by the actor [[Vincent Price]].
