}}

'''''World of Guns: Gun Disassembly''''' is a cross-genre [[Simulation video game|simulation]] and [[Puzzle video game|puzzle]] video game that allows the player to operate and disassemble various [[Firearm|firearms]], as well as other mechanisms like automobiles, [[Armoured fighting vehicle|AFVs]] and aircraft. It was released in 2014 for [[Windows]]<ref name="wog-steampage">{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/app/262410/|title=World of Guns: Gun Disassembly on Steam}}</ref> and [[Facebook]], and has been subsequently ported to [[VK (social networking)|VK.com]] social network, as well as [[OS X]], [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] platforms. The game is a follow-up on the same developer's ''Gun Disassembly'' series, first released in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noble-empire.com/about.php|title=About - Noble Empire Corp. Official Website}}</ref> expanding on the latter's feature set and library of interactive models.

The software can be used as both an interactive firearms reference source and encyclopedia,<ref name="tfb-review">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2014/10/16/world-guns-gun-disassembly/|title=''Johnson, Steve'' World of Guns: Gun Disassembly: My favorite gun app|website=The Firearm Blog|date=October 16, 2014}}</ref> and a [[Casual game|casual]] puzzle game with a goal of disassembling and assembling models in the correct sequence and in the least possible time.

== Gameplay ==
The player is presented with an interactive model of a real-world firearm (or other mechanism) in a 3D environment. Player has complete control of the camera, along with additional viewing options allowing them to explore the inner mechanical design of the piece. These include a multi-layered X-ray view, "trainer [[Cutaway drawing|cutaway]]" mode and several slow-motion settings.

Depending on the game mode, the player is required to either learn the correct operation of the weapon, or perform its disassembly or assembly. Game modes are arranged in the order of increasing complexity, including field-stripping the weapon, complete disassembly of the mechanism, and finally disassembly and assembly against the clock and/or with penalties for incorrect moves. Every model has local and global leaderboards and a set of in-game achievements. The game includes interactive shooting ranges with timed objectives,<ref name="launchparty">{{cite web|url=https://launchpartygaming.com/reviews/pc-reviews/2016/world-guns-gun-disassembly-review/|title=''Nate L.'' World of Guns: Gun Disassembly Review|website=Launch Party Gaming|date=June 11, 2016}}</ref> as well as additional features like gun quizzes and a weapon skin editor.

''World of Guns: Gun Disassembly'' is offered as a [[free-to-play]] title. To unlock the initially unavailable models, a player can either spend in-game credits earned through gameplay, or use [[Microtransaction|microtransactions]]. Bulk [[Downloadable content|DLC]] packs are available, including a lifetime access bundle which gives the user access to all current and future models in the library.<ref name="wog-steampage" />

== Models Library ==
One of the game's principal features is a constantly expanding catalog of animated 3D models that dates back to 2010 (the date of initial ''Gun Disassembly'' app's release). On average, developer Noble Empire has been releasing one to two new models monthly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noble-empire.com/news.php|title=News - Noble Empire Corp. Official Website}}</ref> According to developers, 3D models are drawn and animated using actual weapons, original technical documentation and photographic sources.<ref name="wog-appstore">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/world-of-guns/id1143779751?mt=12|title=World of Guns App Store page|accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> At this time, the ''World of Guns'' library consists of 205 models, with over 23,200 individual animated parts total.<ref name="wog-appstore" /> This includes historical and modern firearms, as well as several artillery pieces, motorcycles, automobiles (including [[Humvee]] and [[DeLorean DMC-12]]), an armored vehicle ([[BMP-3]]) and a [[warbird]] ([[Vought F4U Corsair|F4U Corsair]]). Another set of "bonus" models includes dinosaur and mammal skeletons.

